One possible reason to switch away from the mapper is to eliminate the latency of the DBus IPC latency. However, if we're looking to reduce latency here, we can skip the DBus entirely.

As of [7c1dc7ea0b3e ("pldmd: move to libpldm instance ID alloc/free")][1] we can use the libpldm APIs directly to acquire an appropriate instance ID. A rough sketch of the code is as follows (you'll need to add error handling and such):

```
struct pldm_instance_db *db = NULL;
plmd_instance_id_t iid;

pldm_instance_db_init_default(&db);
...
pldm_instance_id_alloc(db, tid, &iid);
...
/* Do things with `iid` */
...
pldm_instance_id_free(db, tid, iid);
...
pldm_instance_db_destroy(db);
```

And that's it. No DBus at all for allocating an instance ID, and allocations are correctly coordinated across all processes on the system ([here's a blog post with more details on how it works][2]).

If we're going to change this code, I much prefer we fix it properly by removing access to the `pldmd`'s `GetInstanceId` DBus API entirely. Also Rashmica will thank you (as it's one less conversion she will need to do) 😊

[1]: https://github.com/openbmc/pldm/commit/7c1dc7ea0b3eec79518b6dcb9552256bfc1cec15
[2]: https://amboar.github.io/notes/2023/03/29/a-global-pldm-instance-id-allocator-for-libpldm.html
